<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Leymus</i> <i>mollis</i> is dominant or characteristically present in the herbaceous layer with <i>Abronia</i> <i>latifolia</i>, <i>Achillea</i> <i>millefolium</i>, <i>Ambrosia</i> <i>chamissonis</i>, <i>Ammophila</i> <i>arenaria</i>, <i>Artemisia</i> <i>pycnocephala</i>, <i>Cakile</i> spp., <i>Calystegia</i> <i>soldanella</i>, <i>Carpobrotus</i> <i>chilensis</i>, <i>Lathyrus</i> <i>littoralis</i>, <i>Poa</i> <i>douglasii</i> and <i>Poa</i> <i>macrantha</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Herbs < 1 m; cover is open to continuous. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Leymus mollis</i> > 50% relative cover in the herbaceous layer (NatureServe 2007).</li>
		
		<li><i>Leymus mollis</i> is characteristically present in the herbaceous layer (Pickart and Barbour 2007).</li>
		
		<li><i>Leymus mollis</i> > 50% relative cover in the herbaceous layer. <i>Abronia, Ambrosia chamissonis, Artemisia pycnocephala, Cakile</i>, and other herbaceous species may be < 30% relative cover (Buck-Diaz et al. 2021, Sikes et al. 2021).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Bare sand at the seaward margin of coastal dunes. The USFWS Wetland Inventory (1996 national list) recognizes <i>Leymus mollis</i> as a UPL plant. </div>
</div>

        
