<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Leymus mollis </i>is a predominant arctic and boreal species, where it is widespread on arctic shores from Alaska and northern Canada to eastern Asia (ssp. <i>villosissimus</i>) and southward on temperate shores in North America from the California coast, to Hudson Bay, Lake Superior, and Massachusetts (ssp. <i>mollis</i>). Plants are large, erect, somewhat glaucous grasses arising from long, stout rhizomes. Culms are scattered in the bare sand at the leading edge of the beach seaward edge of coastal dunes. The common names, native dune grass and American dune grass, also are used. References also use the name <i>Elymus mollis. </i><br/>
<br/>
Because <i>L. mollis </i>is an obligate psammophyte, it thrives under conditions of active sand accretion of nearshore dunes and upper beaches (Pickart and Barbour 2007). <i>L. mollis </i>and the <i>Abronia umbellata </i>ssp. <i>breviflora </i>(a CNPS list 1B.1 plant) grow in the same habitat as the invasive non-native <i>Ammophila arenaria, </i>which has reduced and replaced these native species over much of their ranges in California. Stands fluctuate between being grass- and herb-dominated. They are generally small (< 0.5 ha) and patchy and intermix with stands of the <i>Abronia latifolia-Ambrosia chamissonis </i>alliance. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
