    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Af, Ah-l). Stands occur on dunes around Monterey Bay (Bluestone 1981) and Morro Bay.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Aa-b, Ad-e, Ag-l). Stands in Humboldt Co. are well studied from Lanphere Dunes north to Clam Beach (Barbour and Johnson 1977, Johnson 1963, LaBanca 1993, Parker 1974, Pickart and Barbour 2007). Stands in MacKerricher State Park in Mendocino Co. on slopes with low exotic cover (CNPS unpublished data 2020). One of the largest known stands is at Abbottâ€™s Lagoon in Point Reyes National Seashore; other stands exist on the Point Reyes Peninsula, San Francisco Peninsula, and around Tomales Bay.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Ba-b). Stands occur in the vicinity of Vandenberg Air Force Base in Santa Barbara Co. (Pickart and Barbour 2007).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Leymus mollis </i>is vulnerable to local extirpation by severe winter storms with associated nearshore sand retreat, and stands have been reduced greatly by non-native plants. Particularly, <i>Ammophila arenaria, </i>or sometimes <i>Carpobrotus edulis, </i>displaces <i>L. mollis </i>if not controlled. The presence of <i>A. arenaria </i>changes dune topography, creating steep foredunes covered with high grass cover that displaces native plants. Pickart and Sawyer (1998) reviewed methods of control. </div>
</div>

    

    

